    <h3>WEEK THREE</h3>
    <p> In today’s lecture, we have been introduced to the concept of Venn diagram, which is a diagram style that uses overlapping circles or other shapes to illustrate the logical relationships between two or more sets of items. Allows users to visualize data in clear, powerful ways. In this case, it helps me to define my website goals (shared goals). 

        Then in group of three, we have created a Venn diagram that has Spongebob' s goals, and the designer goals (our goals), and link them to goals that you share with your user group. 
        
        Subsequently, we created an ordered list of 3-5 linked websites that have an aesthetically pleasing design. And an unordered list of 3-5 fictional characters that we like. 
        
          </p>
        <img src="Venn diagram.png">
        <h3>WEEK FOUR - Planning user journey</h3>
        <p>Today we learnt about what user flow is and how to make a user flow. 

            Then we created a user flow diagram on how Spongebob would navigate through a new website that focused on getting recommended the correct meals and workouts based on his gym goals. 
            
            We created a customer journey map that analysis what users (Spongebob) could be thinking when they navigate through our website based on the user flow diagram. 
            
            In the coding activity today, we learnt how to create a paper box model that consists of margins, borders, padding, and the content inside by using HTML/CSS.  </p>
            <h3>WEEK FIVE -  CSS Grids part 1 </h3>
            <p>Today we talked about hand in details and marking rubrics for assignment one. We did an activity about how to create a layout using flexbox. 

                Here are the user persona, Empathy map, Venn diagram,  User flow diagram and Customer journey map I have created for my user Forrest Gump. </p>
